Now I understand the issue! Looking at your data and the downloaded output, the problem is clear:

**The Issue:**
- Your data has correct order values: "1", "2", "3", "4" for parent items
- Child items have `order: null` and use `priority: "1"` instead
- But the exported data shows "1" for all items in the Order column, including child items that should show their priority value

**Your fix is correct but incomplete.** You need to handle both `order` and `priority` fields in the export callbacks:

```tsx
defaultCsvExportParams: {
  processCellCallback: (params) => {
    if (params.column.getColDef().field === "order") {
      // For items with order, return order value
      if (params.node?.data.order) {
        return params.node?.data.order;
      }
      // For child items without order, return priority value
      if (params.node?.data.priority) {
        return params.node?.data.priority;
      }
    }
    return params.value;
  },
},
defaultExcelExportParams: {
  processCellCallback: (params) => {
    if (params.column.getColDef().field === "order") {
      if (params.node?.data.order) {
        return params.node?.data.order;
      }
      if (params.node?.data.priority) {
        return params.node?.data.priority;
      }
    }
    return params.value;
  },
},
```

This will ensure:
- Parent items (with `tree_data_path` like "1111") export their `order` value
- Child items (with `tree_data_path` like "1112/4147") export their `priority` value
- The exported data will correctly show the sequence/priority structure

