The two code files you shared (QA vs Local) are **identical** — the component code is the same in both environments. So the difference isn't in this file.

The reason it works locally but not in QA is almost certainly a **difference in the `@textile/biz-components` or `@solvasam/bizcomponents` package version** between your local and QA environments.

Specifically, look at the `FormValueSelector` component behavior:

```javascript
// From FormValueSelector in @solvasam/bizcomponents
useEffect(() => {
    if (valueType) {
      setValueTypeState(valueType?.toLowerCase());
    }
    if (lockValueType) {
      const event = {};
      handleToggleChange(event, "ref");  // This sets _value_type to "ref"
    }
}, [handleToggleChange, lockValueType, ...]);
```

When `lockValueType` is `true` (predefined table), this `useEffect` calls `handleToggleChange(event, "ref")` which does `valueTypeHelpers.setValue("ref", false)`. 

The key issue: **Formik's behavior with `setValue` on unregistered fields differs between versions.** 

- In your **local** version of `@textile/biz-components` (or the Formik version it uses), calling `setValue("ref")` on a field that wasn't in the initial values still adds it to the form data — so `382361_value_type` ends up as `"ref"` in the save data.
- In the **QA** version, the field isn't tracked because it was never in the initial values returned by `handleOnBeforePopulate`, so `setValue` either silently fails or the value doesn't persist to the form submission data.

**To confirm:** Check the version of `@textile/biz-components` (and its Formik dependency) deployed to QA vs what you have locally.

**The fix I applied is correct regardless** — by always initializing `_reference_value` and `_value_type` in `handleOnBeforePopulate` for all V/B/T parameters, the fields are properly registered in Formik's initial values, making the behavior consistent across all Formik/library versions. This is the proper approach rather than relying on Formik's undocumented behavior of accepting `setValue` on unregistered fields.

